column1: When will the World Health Organization (WHO) report 40 million or more confirmed cases of COVID-19 in India?
column5: ['Before 1 July 2021', 'Between 1 July 2021 and 31 July 2021', 'Between 1 August 2021 and 31 August 2021', 'Between 1 September 2021 and 30 September 2021', 'Not before 1 October 2021']

Days before the closing date. The Data says it all, again anchoring with the crowd.
This question has been done for a while. Time to resolve.

Hasta el 10 de septiembre del 2021 se han reportado 33,174,954 según who casos de coronavirus desde el inicio de la pandemia, en la actualidad están reportando una media de 37.489 casos diarios, por lo tanto si siguen con esa media, le faltan 181 días aproximadamente para llegar a un total de 40 millones de casos https://graphics.reuters.com/world-coronavirus-tracker-and-maps/es/countries-and-territories/india/ https://covid19.who.int/region/searo/country/in
happy to have been wrong here.

As of September 4th 32,987, 615 in total 45,482 daily as of sept 2nd which appears steady per day. Remaining 25 days of September gives 1,137,050 Which is below the 40 million number for 1st October 2021.
Case count continues to stay low and steady...
32.8M as of Aug 31. 7 day avg is 42.6 k and steady for the last month. daily counts need to surge well past 200k/day to resolve before Oct 1 so I'd say this one is in the bag.
A few indicators to note: - Google mobility trends at transit/public stations ~ pre-pandemics levels - Tests/case decreasing without tests themselves increasing
We’re at 39 million tonight. 8-3-2021
50/50. Like everyone here, just watching the case numbers.

The National institute of Disaster Management has warned of a looming third wave that will peak in October - personally, I can't see it happening just yet as there is little evidence of an increase in most states.

Just a light tweak to reflect the passage of time... September window looking increasingly unlikely with 7-day average now only 30k/day and it needs to average 192k/day. Not impossible though as the April-May crisis escalated fast enough to achieve this (e.g. in the 21 days between 20 April and 11 May 7.7 m cases were added.

Total reported cases are at 32.4M, and daily cases declining from 33K/day. Kerala, the state earlier struggling to contain rising numbers, is now back under 20K/day and Maharashtra (which contributes the second largest number of cases) is also declining. Under 6 weeks to go - case closed.
Can we close this question yet? India has done a pretty good job of responding to the Delta variance after tripping all over themselves for several months.

Long overdue correction that I had put off. My resistance to take a 'mark-to-market' hit to my odds was at least partly rooted in the disbelief that the official cases in India could be so low relative to other countries with significantly higher vaccination rates. Of course, that's ignoring what the question is really asking for - officially reported numbers. One possibility is that, there may be a threshold (of cases) beyond which reported numbers will align with expectations. The other possibility is that the numbers are actually low and we just don't understand why.

32.2m as of Aug 13. 7 day avg of 37.3k and very steady. A massive surge would be needed to cross 40m before Oct 1 now and doesn't seem likely, especially considering the last surge was Delta and there's nothing worse currently on the radar.

Just pulling the September number down a touch to recognise the passage of time... at the time of making this forecast there would need to be an average of >170k cases per day to hit 4m by 30 September. Currently on ~40k/day, so the 170k is by no means impossible but increasingly unlikely. A reasonably cautious attitude seems to be being taken for Independence Day celebrations on 15/8: https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/government-issues-instructions-for-independence-day-celebrations/article35708318.ece
If there is no pronounced rise by August 10, especially in the R-naught, I will chase the last bin to final.

need to follow this a bit more. Important indian holiday/celebrations coming on aug 15. several states report close to tipping point. most states with covid still on some sort of lockdown although it may be partially eased for aug 15. https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/night-curfew-section-144-imposed-in-bengaluru-141-containment-zones-in-city-101628085500765.html https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/no-lockdown-on-saturdays-but-triple-lockdown-if-kerala-tweaks-covid-rules-as-infections-shoot-up-101628071905911.html
A forecasting article: https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/forecaster-who-predicted-indias-covid-peak-sees-new-wave-coming/articleshow/84964264.cms?

Restrictions are currently in place but are steadily easing. To take a benchmark bad scenario from the delta variants rampage during April and May of 2021, around 8-10 Mil cases were confirmed over this 2 month period. There are currently 31 Mil cases. If this upsurge was to repeat, it would take till around the end of September to the beginning of October for this bad scenario to reach roughly 40-Mil cases. Given that nearly half of Indians have had at least one dose of the vaccine and some restrictions are inplace, a FULL repeat of this earlier rampage before the October seems unlikely
sudden increase in cases on 24/7 (79k) vs 7 day average of 38k. however day before was 0. is this just a reporting issue? monitor.

31.3 M, 38K 7-day avg currently. 69 Days to go. Would need to be above 126k to cross 40. Vaccination rates are still low but even during the last surge it took a month to jump like that. So officially, it doesn't look like it'll cross 40M until well past Oct 1 unless there is a revision.. which...

Now down to 7-day rolling average of about ~40k - seems to have levelled off. To reach 4m cases by 31/8 it needs to be the same rate as it as at the peak of the last wave. That seems to be able to be ruled out, esp. with vaccination program progressing steadily. Still keeping some in September though!

Taking the plunge. The lowest 7-day average since the recent peak was yesterday. There would barely be enough time left to reach 40M if cases started going up right now, and instead, they're slightly declining to flat.
As of July 23rd, statistics show a total of 31,293,062 covid infections with a daily (July 23) infection rate of 41,697.

I considered the following figures: As of 20 July, India had some 31.2m COVID cases as per the WHO (so 8.8m less than 40m). For the past 4 weeks, the weekly number of cases stabilized at a lower level, ranging between 268k-361k new cases per week, compared to 2.7m in a week at the peak of the last COVID wave. Looking into India, Pakistan and Bangladesh, previous "low tides" of infection seemed to last between 5-15 weeks. Vaccination is still slow, with 24% of the population receiving the 1st dose according to Reuters.

Cases at around 50k per day. Cumulative about 30m Another 10m at 50k per day is 200 days Cases reported depends on testing and whether there will be another wave in India. India has had 2 waves, so will be interesting to see if this has conferred immunity reducing possible transmission. Feels like not likely to happen before Oct.

Case numbers are still just in decline, and some regions including Maharashtra have I think recently chosen to continue restrictions for another 10 days or more which is encouraging. I think there is more vigilance this time and a greater willingness to continue restrictions as earlier predicted, leaving only Kerala as a major concern with over 13.5k av.7-day case rate and still rising. Apparently over 2/3 Indians now also have some Covid antibody resistance, and even Modi is advocating health over politics. So while there is a justifiable concern over an imminent third wave, I think curbs are likely to be continued or imposed to flatten a repeat of the second wave, and every day case numbers keep declining the time-frame is pushed back further. Updating to: end of July max: 31.6M (-0.2M), August: 33.6M (-0.6M), September: 38.6M (-0.4M)

Good behaviors in the regions. Shutting borders and quarantine with travel from areas with high infection rates. Can't fault the govt response from the outside. But movements are increasing and gatherings are increasing which may lead to super spreader events
Cases are about to plateau briefly and start going up again. I'm still optimistic that states won't let things get as bad as before.
Coming down, just when not IF third wave

Travel restrictions are easing and religious festivals are bringing millions together without covid restrictions. Massive potential for super spreader events. https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-57804713

Ok, if @paulm is at 100%, maybe I'll be bold and inch 2% closer to 100%. I still do fear the possibility that cases could resurge because 1) we're in the middle of the respiratory virus and wedding seasons, and 2) a lot of restrictions are about to be lifted.

Cases are still declining, albeit very slowly. Increasing the probability of the last bin by 1%, decreasing the probability of the 4th bin by 1%. If all restrictions were lifted today, we would expect cases to start to rise nationally within a week. The previous rise in cases offers an upper limit on how fast reported cases would likely rise. If reported cases rose equally fast from today's case rate starting tomorrow, 40M would be reached in about 41 days. But in reality, it would take time for cases to turn around, and cases wouldn't rise as fast because so many more people have some immunity now. Moreover, given recent experiences, I do believe most locations would impose restrictions before cases reached previous levels. There are 77 days left to September 30. The longer cases stay low, the less possible 40M looks before Sept 30.
the second wave has mostly ended so the confirmed case counts have plateaued, but there might be a third wave around October
https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/india/#graph-cases-daily

Case numbers have started falling from the height of case numbers and international attention on the issue. Even at an elevated rate of 1 million per week, this barely scrapes the needed 10 million cases left to hit 40 million by October. Another massive surge would need to occur, and I put the probability of that relatively low given all the resources that are being spent to try to keep people safe.

The wave has been controlled now. If the weekly numbers remain low, there shouldn't be more than 3M more cases (so 34M total). The total number of cases could quickly reach 40M if a similar waves begins, but it seems to me that historically such waves take a few months to start, so I'm betting a wave would not reach peak before October.

WHO can report 40 million cases in one of two ways: 1) a fundamental amendment of the case count due to distrust in the government's reporting, for which there are numerous sources to say that the cases are being unreported (e.g. https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2776292) 2) the official case count reaches 40 million
At this point, even an aggressive resurgence of a new variant would be difficult to break 40M by Oct. 1. Anything less than a 10% weekly increase in cases resolves to bin 5.
I no longer believe cases will reach 40M by 1st October. Every day case numbers continue to decline from now on - however slowly - this option becomes less plausible.
Currently (12th July 2021) WHO reports that India has had 30,752,950 confirmed cases of Covid-19.

30.7m and 42.5k/day avg. It seems we've hit bottom and as much as I think it will go back up it probably won't be before the end of August. 84 days to Sept 30 means 110k/day average until then and as much as I don't expect that in the next few weeks I can't rule it out either.
30.7 million cases now, 291 million vaccinated.

The maximum likely range foreseen for end of September now falls a little short of 40M, based on monthly estimated numbers. End of June actual figure: 30.4M, forecast max end of July: 31.8M, August: 34.2M, September: 39.0M

As of June 29 June, the daily infection rate has decreased to 45.674 from a peak of 414,333 in May 6 during the last (2nd) wave. Assuming a third wave is possible as per the concern in Europe, it would some months (7) to reach another 10 million cases.

Cases may reach a nadir in next two weeks, but case numbers are again marginally lower than earlier forecasts; therefore appearing less likely to reach above 35M through August. This gives more time to manage restrictions if cases rise August/September and a higher range permissible in September while still falling short of 40M.
Ok, 40M cases by Aug 31 isn't realistic. Setting that to 0%. But Sept 30 is still a long ways away, with the peak of the respiratory virus season and the wedding season ahead of us.

30.55M cases recorded so far. 44.6k cases/day and still falling. Only 5 states have seen increases over the past 14 days, and all but one have cases < 1000/day. Kerala has 12k cases/day, and cases there have increased 3% in the past 14 days. Not long ago, only 1 state was seeing increases. So, this has to be watched, but so far, most states are keeping a lid on Covid. At this point, restrictions would have to be fully lifted and spread like that seen in April would need to be allowed, for cases to reach 40M by August 31. I think that is extremely unlikely. If cases were kept at ~50k/day, it would take 189 days to reach 40M. The last bin looks increasingly likely, but it all depends on whether states continue to control spread. https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/world/india-covid-cases.html

I've been Big Wrong on my incremental predictions - almost a perfect parabolic rise and fall in reported cases. We are now at under 50k per day and 30.4m reported cases, even at this pace it will take until Jan 2022 to cross 40m.
Latest 7-day average is under 50k per day so things are still improving, but there is some reduction in restrictions in some places, so further drops in daily average may be less likely.

India has done a great job of flattening the curve. Of course, they can't maintain lockdown measures forever, so I expect new cases to rise again. However, vaccinations are also picking up (currently sitting around 20% of the population with at least 1 dose), so that will go a long way to reducing numbers. Who knows what the next variant will hold, so I'm allowing for some negative surprise in addition to a 3rd wave.
All depends now on any rise in case numbers through August.
I think numbers will flatten at under 50K/day by mid-July and will start rising through August; the outcome may all depend on the rate of change we see in about 6 weeks time.

At the current rate, let's say 50,000 new cases a day (which is on the current high end), it will take six months to cross the 40 million COVID cases mark. India should be applauded for whatever they are doing to get their situation under control (unlike Brazil).
Cases need to be double the current rate for 100 days - looking less likely every week

I guess I'll essentially go with the crowd here for a while. Only 1 state has increasing cases, and that's at <100/day. So far, so good. The time of greatest danger is July and August, so we're not out of the woods yet.

I'm expecting the same overall pattern as before, but case rates have reduced marginally further (better) than I'd expected. Using a monthly est. as a benchmark to gauge from; Forecast from beginning of June: End of June 31M, July 32.5-33.5M, Aug 35.5-38M Updating to: End of June 30.5M, July 31.8-32.5M, Aug 34-37M, Sept 37-41

As of June 25, number of confirmed cases is 30.1M; and since 2 months ago, it's on a decreasing trend constantly. My hope is that with some help, in getting vaccination, we won't be seeing a major spike for a while. Estimated total number of cases by October 2021 is about 32M. That is, expecting next 3 months to be like 2021 Q1 for India.
When you want the best answer go to the source at: https://covid19.who.int/region/searo/country/in It's a race against time, India quickly needs to be highly vaccinated.

Currently 30 million cases Need 100k per day to beat 1 Oct Currently 53k per day and dropping UK was in a similar position (shape not number) 1.5 months ago and it is now lifting again but this is because they have this variant My feeling is that they would need a new more infectious strain to get back to 100k/day I want to increase more but I am wary of overconfidence and how quickly things could change over 3 months A pre-mortem scenario is that infections drop to 30k/day stable on average and Modi says that he has beaten the virus and that Independence day should be a national celebration (to boost his party's election year polling) 30k/day for 54 days now 32 mil cases. The mass gathering skyrocket Delta+ (following the same trajectory magnitude as Delta from 15 March onwards), by 15 September it is at 175k cases per day and 1st Oct is at 400k cases/day (same as Delta) adding another 8 mil cases. - And there is our 40,000,000 cases!

30M a/o June 23, 200k below where I thought a week ago. I thought numbers had bottomed out a week ago but they've fallen another 20% which is great news. I'm going down on my average daily significantly, so say 70k/day until Aug 1 means under 33M by that date. Aug 1 - Aug 30, even at 100k/day would fall well short of 40m unless the official estimate is significantly increased from the last wave. Sept could still happen if left unchecked but lets hope things keep looking good

Based on local but possibly biased feedback, I am quite skeptical of the reported numbers generally and specifically about the speed of decline in cases. But, be that as it may, I do need to adjust my estimates based on official numbers. If we look at google mobility trends for India for the past 4 weeks, public transport levels are up 30 percentage points, time spent at home reduced 20 percentage points and most tellingly, retail and recreation - a proxy for letting your hair down was up 25 percentage points. Of course, these categories have different base levels and the usual caveats apply, but 10m in 70 days seems reasonably likely especially if the vaccination levels don't increase rapidly.
reduced chance in next 2 months
So far, so good at getting cases down. Still, respiratory virus season goes through September, and wedding season is coming up. India will need to keep a lid on the virus.

Daily case rates keep tracking down with 7-day average below 60k/day as of 21 June. But I can't completely rule out the possibility of a repeat of April-May (see my pre-mortem in the team discussion for this question!)
Happy to start reducing

India already has almost 30 million Covid cases with an average of 70,000 daily in the last week, which projected in the future brings to an estimate 3,5 months before additional 10 million people will be infected, without however taking into account specific epidemiological models used to calculate the rapidity of the transmission rate.

third wave expected during monsoon season similar to peak in Sep 2020, current total 30 mill cases with 70k daily cases, in Sep 2020 peak 400k daily cases, vaccination coverage as mitigating factor still low at 270 mill doses in population of 1.366 bill, aggravating factor of variant

June 16 sees 67k new cases with 74k avg, 29.7m total. Numbers look to be bottoming out as the restrictions ease. Numbers have fortunately fallen lower than I had expected and vaccination rates are doing well. It'll likely be another week at these numbers before climbing again so June 23 should see 30.2m which is below my guess from last week. June 30 will likely be ~31m. Say it floats in the 120k/day range for the following month that's ~35m by the end of July. Then August would need over 150k/day avg to cross 40m before the end, which is looking much less likely now. Sept. is still looking most likely but if vaccinations accelerate it could be pushed later. To make it past Oct 1 the daily totals have to be below 97k until then period. It should be doable but will depend on how the next few weeks with fewer restrictions go.

Bangladesh appears to be ahed of India with respect to timing of COVID-19 waves by some three to four weeks (is the DELTA variant in fact a mutation originating in Bangladesh without recognition there due to a lack of surveillance?).

at current rate it would require 150 days Would require double the rate for next 75 days to reach 1 sep. A small spike in Nashik dropped again. I think that it would require a large change in community behavior to swing the rates because they already have the most contagious strain currently around. Independence day is the only major holiday in this period which would normally bring parades and mass public mingling. This could impact it.

Data still tracking down. 7-day average is ~80k/day and falling; 105 days to 1st October, at that rate means 8.4m more cases, which would be just under 40m total. So, after 1 October now seems most likely result, with the scenarios earlier than September really only likely if something catastrophic happens.
Are on the other side of the curve, if they stay under 50,000/day it looks better, although could have a nothe wave.

10 m cases in 45 days looks extremely unlikely, however there are reasons to expect a "third wave" spread between Aug & Sep - Vaccination rates haven't increased and mutated variants getting more time to spread - Human tendency to wish for life to get back to normal - postponed weddings, projects will be squeezed into the next available window (lifting of lockdowns) - tests/confirmed case dropping again
The hardest thing about this Q is remembering that it depends on what the Indian government reports, and not what is almost certainly true.
Working from an earlier forecast as a guide for monthly figures. Adding in an approx for the end of September; Sep 37.5-42M

Reconsidering. Suppose 30.2M and 50k cases/day reached by June 25. 9.8M cases to go to reach 40M. 67 days to Aug 31: 9800k cases / 67 days = 146k/day 97 days to Sep 30: 9800k cases / 97 days = 101k/day When restrictions ease, how far will different regions let cases go up before tighter restrictions are imposed again? Especially given that most locations seem to take a reactive approach, and knowing that when tighter restrictions are imposed, cases won't be affected until almost a week later.

29.51M total as of 6/13. 85.8k/day. 10.49M to go to reach 40M. To reach 40M by 8/31: 79 days, need >=133k/day. To reach 40M by 9/30: 109 days, need >= 96k/day. Different places are lifting restrictions. The decline is slowing. I don't think 40k by 8/31 is likely, but I am not as optimistic as the crowd about September.
India is getting their COVID outbreak under control, as represented in the rapid decline in new COVID cases. It is possible that India will not hit 40 million cases this calendar year.
The number of daily cases continue decreasing

rate per day now under 85 thousand according to WHO. total confirmed cases at 29.4 million. at current rate, 124 days before 40 M infections, which would put it after 1/10/21. will need to watch rates to make sure it stays low.

The country is down to 84000 cases per day and dropping (although slower). If it stabilised at this rate it would take 136 days to reach 40m cases (not before 1 Oct) Average of 105000/day are required to beat 1 Oct No districts are yet showing any increase in infections that could indicate a possible new wave Would need 152k/day to beat 1 Sep. Looking at last outbreak it could take over a month to get up to 150k from the indication of an outbreak. so would probably need to hit 200k+ which is unlikely. I will continue to trend down my september each week that there isn't any indication of a new outbreak.

The decline is slowing. Optimistic that cases/day will keep declining towards 50k/day and will be kept under ~100k/day to 150k/day. Hedging against the possibility that cases intermittently go up to ~200k/day. 100 days left to Sept 30; an average of 96k/day would get to 40M by Sept 30. I'm not as sanguine as the crowd about the last bin; my Brier score will probably suffer for it later, but I think there's more risk here of cases averaging around 100k/day or even a bit higher.
Just a slight tweak to acknowledge the growing potential for the 'not before 1 October' option

The decline continues. 40M before Aug 31 is looking less likely. If government restrictions let up too quickly, Sept 30 is still possible, as now through September is the peak season for Covid spread. I'm optimistic that cases/day will decline to ~50k/day, and 30M will be reached over the next 8 to 10 days. I'm also optimistic that from that point, if enough restrictions are left in place or put in place intermittently, then cases/day can be kept between 50k and 100k.

Hard to predict with any accuracy yet, but I think things will continue to look better during June, with a low in July, but by August some regional measures will be re-introduced to prevent cases rising too rapidly. Still with forecast from 5th June as a benchmark; end of June 31M, July 32.5-33.5M, Aug 35.5-38M

I think a low will be reached through July at ~60-80K, before cases increase again. The question for me then becomes at what point regional measures will be re-introduced to prevent another wave through August. I find this harder to predict, but I think measures will be taken as cases head towards 150-200K, slowing the increase. Using my forecast from 5th as a benchmark for now; end of June 31M, July 32.5-33.5M, Aug 35.5-38M

re. @belikewater and @Ravi-Ivaturi1574726980 's comments. Seems making it past Oct 1 is a longer shot and cases are likely to come back up over the next month as restrictions ease. Some are still in place for another week so the next two weeks should show some stability before trending up again. With that extrapolated out, they'll be at ~30.5 June 23 and I wouldn't be surprised to see numbers over 150k/day again shortly after. Say 32m June 30. Then?? at 200k/day that puts it to mid August, which doesn't seem too far fetched although the regional govts will hopefully be more actively restricting flare ups. I seems likely late Aug/Early Sept at this rate. I'll be an optimist and edge slightly for Sept

The decline in cases is slowing down. With seasonality favoring spread through mid September and restrictions being lifted, perhaps 40M could be reached earlier. It looks like cases could possibly level out at as high as ~100k/day over the next few days. At that rate, it takes 110 days to add 11M cases; 84 days remaining before Aug. 31. If cases were to increase a bit for a while, 40M could be reached before Aug. 31. And as @Ravi-Ivaturi1574726980 points out, wedding season is July & August. And there are 114 days before Sept 30. I assign only 1% to the July 1 to 31 bin because for 40M cases to be reached over the next 53 days, cases would have to average 206k or higher, and that would require cases getting very out of control again. I don't think state authorities will let that happen after their experiences with the recent surge, but maybe I am wrong. Update 6/10: Looks like cases will make it to <100k, maybe even to ~50k. Probably somewhere in between.

While the cases have fallen sharply, it's important to note - lockdown started to ease across the country -which should increase mobility and potentially more infections - July & Aug are typically wedding months - vaccination rates ~ 13%.

Drastic drop in new cases lately! But states are starting to reopen (everything can't stay locked down indefinitely) so I expect case rates will stabilize and maybe start to go up again soon. On the other hand, vaccination rates are starting to accelerate.

Recent trends of daily cases have dropped enormously since my last forecast, and vaccination and lessons-learned should keep this trend going. Plus, I wonder if the Indian government will suppress data going to WHO if things get bad again!
Surge is declining - at current rates it would take more than 100 days, at half current rates 200 days to add 10Mill cases. But India opening up again - will this start a new wave?
Update 6/9: Total cases at 29.0M as of June 7. Will reach 30M by approx June 17.

It's looking more likely to me that the decline will slow. Looking at 2020, it took 40 days for cases to fall from a peak of 93k in mid September to <50k - and that was as seasonal pressures were waning. So, let's suppose that it takes 2 months for cases to fall from their current 123k/day to 50k/day (which might not happen at all, as cases could rise again or decline more slowly or faster). This would add in the ballpark of 5.2M cases to the current total of 28.9M, for a total of 34.1M by Aug. 7. At 50k/day after that, another 1.2M would be added by the end of August, followed by 1.5M by the end of Sept, for a total of 36.8M. That's *if* sufficient restrictions are kept in place to keep cases declining, even as seasonality makes spread more likely.

The decline seems to be starting to slow down. The decline has been slightly slower than the rise to the peak and is getting a bit slower. It should also be kept in mind that spread will be most likely over the next 2 months because of seasonality. Perhaps 100k cases/day will now be reached over the next 1-2 weeks? Need to watch closely to see whether cases/day start to plateau. This slowing in the rate of decline makes reaching and maintaining 50k cases/day less likely, so I'm updating. 11.31M cases to go to reach 40M. * To reach 40M by July 31, 56 days left in forecast, 202k cases/day (cases would have to get out of control again) * To reach 40M by Aug 31, 87 days left in forecast, 130k cases/day (not impossible) * To reach 40M by Sept 30, 117 days left in forecast, 97k cases/day
28.7m. 11.3m for 40m Current rate = 120k per day @200k per day = 56 days = Aug @150k per day = 75 days = Sept @100k per day = 113 days

It is now slightly easier to justify keeping restrictions in place than it is to ease them prematurely, and as a consequence they could reach 60k/day by end June. Pressure to get back to business should be reflected in case numbers through July, when I’m expecting them to flatten. Some increase still looks inevitable after that but to what extent? By then they could be tempered partially by vaccines and any other regional measures reintroduced. June: 31M, July: 32.5-33.5M, Aug: 35.5-38M
28,574,350 reported by WHO. 11,425,650 remaining. 145k cases per day and still dropping.

5 days per 50k/day reduction in the 7-day average of cases/day, slower than the upward rise in cases. By June 7, India should record ~100k cases/day. Will states keep enough restrictions in place to reach 50k cases/day in the near future? Will the decline from 100k cases/day to 50k cases/day take 5 days or longer? Total now is 28.44M. By June 7, India will likely be at ~29.07M cases. 11M more to reach 40M. * At an average of 100k cases/day, 1M/10 days, or 3M/month. 40M could just be reached before Oct. 1. * At an average of 50k cases/day, 1M/20 days, or 1.5M/month. 40M would not be reached until after Oct. 1 or perhaps never, if enough vaccinations are given. But, Covid cases could surge at any moment if restrictions are lifted too soon, because the virus is still spreading rampantly in many locations throughout the country. Also, now through October is the season in which Covid is likely to spread the most in India based on last year's experience with Covid and previous experience with all other respiratory viruses. So, this question is really about whether India will keep enough restrictions in place to limit virus spread. I suspect, though, that most or all state and regional governments do not want to repeat the recent surge and so will try to keep cases at a lower level. So, I am weighting later dates more.
You know when your GPS says "rerouting" . . . yeah this is one of those.
In the last month (May) there has been a reduction of the Daily Covid cases in India

More than anything else I think it will be the timing of easing restrictions, and how widespread these are, they determines the outcome of this one. Modi will likely push to open up quickly for manufacturing and the ‘economy’ while there may be regions that keep restrictions for longer while vaccine distribution and uptake improves. Hence the outcome is still difficult to pin down accurately. But it does seem more likely to stretch from September into October now, as it will be easier to keep restrictions in place by virtue of them having been established, and by being demonstrably effective.
28.31m as of June 1, 164k 7d average with continued decline.

In India, from 3 January 2020 to 5:06pm CEST, 1 June 2021, there have been 28,175,044 confirmed cases of COVID-19 with 331,895 deaths, reported to WHO. As of 25 May 2021, a total of 200,494,991 vaccine doses have been administered.

Businesses in Maharashtra are getting desperate to reopen their businesses. The state is going to keep many restrictions in place for at least 2 more weeks. I'm sure similar dynamics are playing out all over the country, with some states inclined to keep restrictions in place in some localities longer than others. If Maharashtra keeps restrictions in place for 2 more weeks, then cases there would likely fall to somewhere around 10k/day, a bit less than 1/6 of the peak. Suppose that cases in India fall to ~1/7 of the peak, say, to somewhere between 50k/day and 60k/day, and then are allowed to oscillate around those numbers. Then India would be at ~31M or 32M by mid June, and 40M would not be reached by Oct. 1. I'm going to weight that possibility a bit higher.

Confirmed cases are falling a bit more slowly than they rose but are thankfully still falling fast. In perhaps a bit over 2 weeks, the country will hopefully report ~100k cases/day. At that point, the total number of recorded cases would be just under 30M. If cases plateaued at 100k/day, then India would see 40M cases in September. If lockdowns were lifted too early, cases would easily rise again. If lockdowns continue and cases keep falling, cases could plateau around 50k/day or less. But it should be kept in mind that the seasonal peak is likely to be around mid-September, so if restrictions are lifted too early, we can expect cases to come roaring back. In other words, substantial restrictions will likely need to remain in place through September to prevent a resurgence. Then the question will be whether regions around the country will be able to continue such restrictions.

Today, there are 24.6 million confirmed cases (https://covid19.who.int/region/searo/country/in). Looking at the daily cases, India appears to have hit their second peak (which occurred ~6 May with ~412,262 cases confirmed in a single day). Their first peak resolved at the same rate it grew (bell curve) therefore I forecast that by 29 July 2021 they will have hit 32.1 million cases and then plateau from that point. I do not believe they will hit 40 million by October if they take the same measures that saw the first wave resolve and vaccinations continue. Of-course I am concerned about emerging variants that may evade vaccine effectiveness, and also 'corrective reporting' which would see the numbers surge to better reflect Covid-19 spread over the last 12 months. Some reports suggest that the actual number of Covid-19 cases in India could be 10 times what WHO is currently reporting (https://scroll.in/article/994619/india-is-undercounting-covid-19-deaths-heres-how-to-work-around-the-problem, https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2021/04/30/992451165/india-is-counting-thousands-of-daily-covid-deaths-how-many-is-it-missing). Should there be a correction, we may find India hit 40 million cases back in September 2020. Until that happens, or something catastrophic occurs, I do not believe that India will see 40 million cases before 1 October 2021.

I don't know what to expect right now. The previous forecast for India/SE Asia was clear: the authorities would do too little, too late. Now there are many restrictions, but will they lift them too soon? Moreover, restrictions are imposed in many places, but spread in areas outside larger cities is increasing, and such spread will largely go unmeasured and not enter into this forecast. In part because of ongoing spread outside larger cities, as soon as restrictions are lifted, cases will come roaring back. Will the authorities in different places lift restrictions in 2 weeks, 1 month, 2 months, longer? The federal government imposed extensive restrictions for long durations in 2020, but is there sufficient political will for comparable restrictions now? And restrictions would need to be imposed for longer time periods now because cases are at a much higher level now. I just don't have a feel for what will happen yet. The only thing that is becoming increasingly clear is that 40M will likely not be reached by July 31. The average cases/day would need to be ~199k/day for the remaining 77 days before July 31 for India to reach 40M cases. India will likely see ~200k/day in ~11 +/-1 day, probably adding just under 3.5M to the total number of cases. Then cases/day would need to stay under an average of about 180k/day until July 31 to stay under 40M. One smaller problem is that the Indian gov't has relied on spectacularly amateurish modeling efforts to guide its actions, and it's not clear whether that will change. https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/government-backed-model-to-predict-pandemic-rise-and-ebb-lacks-foresight-scientists/article34479503.ece The larger problem is that the government will face giant pressure from all sides to keep things closed and to open things up, and it will likely do whatever it thinks at the moment will be the best course for improving the re-election chances of BJP candidates. So this is really a forecast about Indian politics, and I'm not sure yet which way the wind will blow.

Several factors seem pertinent for a forecast that is likely several weeks into the future.

Expecting temporary restrictions to have a dramatic but short-lived affect, combined with scale of the issues and population size prolonging the downward curve. Forecast to reach 40M around the first 2 weeks of July, but the timeline is prone to significant shifts dependant on changing conditions, so I think it will be difficult to gauge accurately for a few weeks yet.

We seem primed for week-over-week cases to see first declines in the next 7-10 days. Unless such declines are very insignificant, Bin1 will quickly cease to be an option. Outside view is that the decay of surges in most countries is somewhere between symmetrical and lognormal in shape. India may prove to break that pattern, but they would have to do so in striking fashion to hit Bins1 or Bin2.

How big is India's epidemic going to get? Cases are still growing, but testing is leveling off and nearing saturation. Overall test positivity rate is 21% for the country, 32% in New Delhi (down from a peak of 36%), and varies across states; it's as high as 62% in Rajasthan, and as low as 5% in Mizoram. Because testing is nearing saturation, it's hard to know what's really going on. There does appear to be an inflection point in the 7day average of cases/day somewhere around April 16 to 21, but it's hard to know whether that's real. Actual cases could be continuing to climb exponentially out of control. Currently, total at 21.49M, with 390k cases/day and still slightly climbing. Obviously, most cases are being missed, but confirmed cases still give us a useful measure of the size of the problem. In the press, I see speculation that cases in New Delhi and Maharashtra will likely peak in May, other places in June. I'm not sure I see why they should peak in May. Anyway, 18.51M to go to get to 40M. 55 days left before July 1; would require 337k cases/day to reach 40M by July 1. On April 6, there were 93k cases/day (7day average), so things can go up and down very quickly. I suspect we have weeks more to go, though, before the epidemic in India truly turns around. If one estimates that India is underestimating deaths by ~10x, then they have reached about as many deaths as a proportion of the population as the US has. But they don't have nearly enough vaccinations or control measures to slow this down yet. I think India will easily reach 30M cases by July 1. If the epidemic peaks in the next couple weeks or so, then 40M cases may not be reached by July 1. But if it peaks around June 1 or after, then I think 40M is assured, unless they run out of testing supplies. I think the peak of the epidemic for the country as a whole may not be reached until sometime in June. On the other hand, areas outside major cities may have limited testing capabilities, so the true peak may not show up in the testing data. Still, I think it's very likely that India will reach 40M cases before July 1. https://time.com/6045791/india-covid-forecast
